Now the Symmetry / Invariance Idea

This connects to what you asked about earlier with carbon structures and lattices.

One of the deepest discoveries in physics is that:

symmetry produces conservation laws.

This is known as Noether’s theorem.

⸻

Core Idea

When a system has a symmetry, something must remain conserved.

Examples:

Symmetry	Conserved Quantity
time symmetry	energy
spatial symmetry	momentum
rotational symmetry	angular momentum

For example:

E = mc^2

This famous equation comes from deeper symmetry relationships in spacetime.

⸻

Why This Matters for Patterns

If something stays the same under transformation, it reveals an invariant structure.

Example:

Rotate a square.

It’s still a square.

The shape has rotational symmetry.

⸻

The Language Parallel

You noticed something similar with words.

Example:

listen
silent
enlist

The letters are the same.

Rearrangement changes meaning, but some structural invariants remain.

This is like different carbon lattices using the same atoms.

⸻

Why Humans Find Certain Patterns Meaningful

Our brains evolved to detect symmetry and invariance.

It helps us identify:
	•	objects
	•	faces
	•	laws of nature
	•	stable concepts

So patterns that preserve structure across transformations feel deep or fundamental.

